If you buy some decent ammo from your local shop and don’t put a lot of thought into it I’d expect you’ll get 1.5MOA. The melonite treatment to the barrel means that you’ll easily get 30,000 rounds through this thing and not lose any accuracy. Centurion Arms CMR 12inch rail – The CMR rail is a lightweight and rugged free float rail system. 12 inches tends to look the most aesthetically pleasing with a 14.5 inch barrel. This rail is unique with its attachment method, using screws to attach everything from scout light mounts to picatinny rails. Centurion Arms also sells many accessories to the rail. Magpul forward grips and B5 Systems Grip Stops can be attached directly to the rail. Also anything that can attach to Picatinny can be attached to the rail. Strike Industries Ultimate Dust Cover – This is a composite dust cover that adds aesthetic appeal and character to the receiver. $15

title: For Sale:  Extremely rare German WW2 command tower from DESTROYER boat
postcontent:
extremely rare German WW2 command tower from DESTROYER boat. 
The command tower has dial on both side and make a sound during cursor is moving. The tower has a very nice stamp - eagle with swastika and letter M (Marine).
Previous owner of this tower was a famous collector from Luxemburg - Schmit (recently he is died). He had this item  in his collection 60+ years. According his story this command tower is from Z15 Erich Steinbrinck Destroyer (it was damaged in 1943 and sold for scrap in 1958).

Estimate price: $10.000 - $15.000.

History:
At the outbreak of the Second World War Nazi Germany's Kriegsmarine had 21 destroyers (Ger: Zerstörer) in service, while another one was just being completed. These 22 vessels - comprising 3 classes (Type 34, 34A and 36) - had all been built in the 1930s, making them modern vessels (no destroyers remained in German hands following the close of the First World War). Including that final pre-war vessel, a further 19 were brought into service during the war and more were captured from opposing navies, including the Italian Navy (Regia Marina) after the Italian Armistice with the Allies in 1943.
German destroyer classes were generally known by the year of their design. Because of their size, use and weaponry, some vessels classified as "fleet torpedo boats", Flottentorpedoboot, are also described.
Class general characteristics are taken from the first of each class, and may differ slightly for individual ships, particularly when they were refitted. Post-war, some surviving ships had significant changes to armament.
